1. What are control statements in Java?

Control statements determine the order in which program statements are executed.

Types:

Selection Statements (if, if-else, switch)
Iteration Statements (for, while, do-while)
Jump Statements (break, continue, return)
2. What is the difference between if and switch?
if	switch
Works with conditions and relational operators	Works with fixed values
Can evaluate ranges	Cannot evaluate ranges directly
Slower for many conditions	Faster for multiple choices
3. When should you use a switch statement?

Use switch when you need to select one option from many fixed choices based on a single variable.

switch(day){
    case 1: System.out.println("Monday");
    break;
}
4. What is the difference between while and do-while?
while	do-while
Condition checked first	Condition checked after execution
May execute zero times	Executes at least once
5. What is an infinite loop?

A loop that never terminates.

while(true){
    System.out.println("Hello");
}
6. What is the difference between break and continue?
break	continue
Terminates the loop	Skips current iteration
Control moves outside loop	Control goes to next iteration
7. Can break be used outside a loop?

No. Using break outside a loop or switch causes a compile-time error.

8. Can continue be used in a switch statement?

No, unless the switch is inside a loop.

9. What is the purpose of the return statement?

return exits a method and optionally returns a value.

int add(int a, int b){
    return a + b;
}
